The agencies say richer countries already appeared to be hoarding vaccines.  Monkeypox is a viral disease that causes flu-like symptoms and skin lesions. It is endemic in parts of Africa but has also recently been reported in countries with no history of human transmission, including Ghana, Morocco and South Africa. The World Health Organisation (WHO) Director for Africa, Dr Matshidiso Moeti, says what happened in the early days of the COVID-19 vaccine rollout when Africa watched on the sidelines as other countries snapped up limited supplies must not be allowed to recur. Moeti has warned that richer countries are already appearing to be hoarding Monkeypox vaccines. The WHO Director says what happened in the early days of the COVID-19 vaccine rollout when Africa watched on the sidelines as other countries snapped up limited supplies must not be allowed to recur. She adds that Monkeypox vaccines are in short supply globally and there have been no donations to countries on the continent. --SABC/Reuters--